"response_text": "The average initial risk attitude of the social learning agents remains constant at 0.0074 from the beginning to the end of the simulation. Throughout the 100 time steps, the metric shows no deviation, maintaining this exact value without any observable increase or decrease. This indicates that the agents' baseline disposition to deviate from livestock recommendations is static and does not evolve over time within this model configuration. For decision makers, this stability suggests that risk tolerance is an unchanging attribute in this specific scenario. Consequently, interventions designed to influence grazing decisions cannot rely on the agents naturally becoming more or less risk-averse; instead, external management strategies must account for this fixed behavioral tendency."
}

